    {
      "id": 328016,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "Formaldehyde, H<sub>2</sub>C<span data-math=\"\\text{=}\"></span>O, is known to all biologists because of its usefulness as a tissue preservative. When pure, formaldehyde trimerizes to give trioxane, C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>6</sub>O<sub>3</sub>, which, surprisingly enough, has no carbonyl groups. Only one monobromo derivative (C<sub>3</sub>H<sub>5</sub>BrO<sub>3</sub>) of trioxane is possible. Propose a structure for trioxane.",
